SOP-001  |  Opening the Terminal
LEARNING OBJECTIVES
By the end of this SOP you will be able to:
Locate the fnf-agents project folder on your Windows 11 machine
Open PowerShell directly inside the correct folder using the address bar method
Verify the terminal prompt confirms you are in the right location
Explain why the terminal must be opened from the correct folder


Purpose
Open PowerShell in the correct project folder before running any agent
Why it matters
The .env file containing all API keys only loads when PowerShell is opened from the fnf-agents folder. Opening from anywhere else means agents cannot authenticate and will fail immediately.
Time required
30 seconds


Steps
Open File Explorer — press Windows key + E
Navigate to: C:\Projects\FunnyNotFunny\fnf-agents\
Click the address bar at the top of the File Explorer window
Type: powershell — then press Enter
A blue PowerShell window opens
Confirm the prompt shows exactly: PS C:\Projects\FunnyNotFunny\fnf-agents>

NOTE: If the prompt shows PS C:\Windows\System32> or any other path — close it and repeat from Step 1. The folder path in the prompt must match your fnf-agents folder.

PRACTICE EXERCISE  —  Opening the Terminal
Scenario:
You are starting a new work session and need to run the Research Agent to research wolf conservation in the Pacific Northwest. Before you can run any agent you must open the terminal correctly.
Your Tasks:
Close any open PowerShell windows
Open File Explorer and navigate to your fnf-agents folder
Open PowerShell using the address bar method described in this SOP
Verify the prompt shows the correct path
Type: python --version and press Enter to confirm Python is working
Success Criteria:
PowerShell prompt shows PS C:\Projects\FunnyNotFunny\fnf-agents>
python --version returns Python 3.x.x without errors
No errors or warnings appear when opening the terminal


KNOWLEDGE CHECK
Answer these before moving to the next SOP:
1.  Why must PowerShell be opened from the fnf-agents folder specifically?
2.  What does the correct prompt look like when the terminal is open in the right location?
3.  What happens if you open PowerShell from the Start Menu and then navigate to the folder manually?

Answers are in Appendix A at the end of this manual.


SOP-002  |  Running the Research Agent
LEARNING OBJECTIVES
By the end of this SOP you will be able to:
Run the Research Agent with a topic of your choice from the command line
Read and interpret the agent loop output — understanding what each line means
Locate the research brief saved to the output/ folder
Identify the cause area connections in a research brief
Explain the difference between running the agent with and without Tavily configured


Purpose
Research a topic and save a structured brief to the output/ folder
Prerequisites
Terminal open in fnf-agents folder (SOP-001 complete), ANTHROPIC_API_KEY and TAVILY_API_KEY set in .env
Output
Markdown research brief saved to output/ folder
Time required
2-5 minutes depending on topic complexity


Understanding the Agent Loop Output
When the Research Agent runs you will see output like this in PowerShell:

[Loop 1] Thinking...
[Tool] Calling: web_search
       Input:  { "query": "wetlands North America 2024" }
       Result: Search results for: wetlands...
[Loop 2] Thinking...
[Done] Task complete after 4 loop(s)

Each line tells you what Claude is doing. Thinking means Claude is deciding what to do next. Tool Calling means it is running a search or saving a file. Done means the task is complete.

Steps
Open terminal using SOP-001
Run the command below — replace the topic with your subject:

python run_agents.py --agent research --topic "your topic here"

Watch the output — you will see 3-5 search loops run automatically
When you see [Done] Task complete — the brief has been saved
Open File Explorer and navigate to C:\Projects\FunnyNotFunny\fnf-agents\output\
Open the .md file in Notepad or VS Code to review the research brief

NOTE: The agent runs 3-5 web searches automatically without any input from you. The more specific your topic, the more focused the research will be.

PRACTICE EXERCISE  —  Research Agent — First Run
Scenario:
The Funny not Funny content team needs a research brief on the impact of microplastics on marine wildlife. This will be used to draft a blog post connecting animal welfare and environmental justice.
Your Tasks:
Open the terminal using SOP-001
Run the research agent with the topic: microplastics marine wildlife impact
Watch the full output and count how many tool calls are made
When complete, open the research brief in the output/ folder
Read the brief and identify: primary cause area, secondary cause area connections, and 2 story angles suggested
Success Criteria:
Agent completes without errors and shows [Done] Task complete
A .md file appears in the output/ folder
Research brief contains Key Facts, Why It Matters, and Story Angles sections
You can identify at least one connection between cause areas in the brief
You can name 2 specific story angles suggested by the agent


PRACTICE EXERCISE  —  Research Agent — Topic Variation
Scenario:
Now practise running the research agent with a different topic to build familiarity with the command.
Your Tasks:
Run the research agent for a second topic of your choice from FNF's cause areas
Suggested topics: UNDRIP Indigenous sovereignty, factory farming water pollution, MMIW crisis Canada
Compare the two research briefs — which cause areas does each one touch?
Note the filename format used for each saved brief
Success Criteria:
Second research brief saved successfully to output/ folder
You can explain how the filename relates to the topic
You can identify how the two briefs differ in cause area coverage


KNOWLEDGE CHECK
Answer these before moving to the next SOP:
1.  What does [Loop 3] Thinking... mean when you see it in the terminal output?
2.  Where are research briefs saved after the agent completes?
3.  What is the difference in research quality when Tavily is configured versus when it is not?
4.  Why does the agent run multiple web searches rather than just one?

Answers are in Appendix A at the end of this manual.


SOP-003  |  Running the WordPress Publishing Agent
LEARNING OBJECTIVES
By the end of this SOP you will be able to:
Run the WordPress Agent to transform a research brief into a draft post
Read the agent output to confirm the post was created and note the Post ID
Locate the draft post in WordPress Admin
Explain why posts are always created as drafts and never published automatically
Identify the FNF brand standards applied by the agent


Purpose
Transform a research brief into a WordPress draft post
Prerequisites
Research brief in output/ folder, WordPress Application Password in .env, Permalinks set to Post name
Output
Draft post in WordPress Admin — Posts > All Posts
Time required
1-3 minutes


What the Agent Does
The WordPress Agent performs five tasks in sequence: lists available research files, reads the most recent brief, checks WordPress categories, checks recent posts for duplicates, then creates the draft post via the WordPress REST API.

Steps
Confirm a research brief exists in output/ (run SOP-002 first if needed)
Open terminal using SOP-001
Run the command:

python run_agents.py --agent wordpress

Watch the output — the agent will show 5-6 loops
Look for the success message and note the Post ID:

Draft post created successfully!
   Post ID: 291
   Status:  Draft

Write down the Post ID — you will need it to publish
Go to funnynfunny.com/wp-admin > Posts > All Posts
Confirm the draft post appears with a Draft label

NOTE: Always note the Post ID from the terminal output immediately. If you miss it, run python check_posts.py to retrieve it.

PRACTICE EXERCISE  —  WordPress Agent — Create a Draft
Scenario:
You have just completed a research brief on microplastics and marine wildlife using SOP-002. Now you need to turn that brief into a WordPress draft post ready for editorial review.
Your Tasks:
Open the terminal using SOP-001
Run the WordPress agent
Watch the full output and identify which research file the agent chose
Record the Post ID from the success message
Log into funnynfunny.com/wp-admin and find the draft post
Read the first paragraph of the post and check it against the FNF brand voice rules
Success Criteria:
WordPress agent completes without errors
You have the Post ID written down
Draft post appears in WordPress Admin > Posts > All Posts
Post title is compelling and under 60 characters
First paragraph opens with a fact or question, not guilt or alarmist language
Post ends with a clear call to action


KNOWLEDGE CHECK
Answer these before moving to the next SOP:
1.  Why does the WordPress Agent always create posts as drafts instead of publishing directly?
2.  What should you do immediately after the WordPress Agent completes successfully?
3.  What WordPress setting must be configured to Post name for the agent to work?
4.  What does the agent check before creating the post to avoid duplicate content?

Answers are in Appendix A at the end of this manual.


SOP-004  |  Publishing via WordPress Admin
LEARNING OBJECTIVES
By the end of this SOP you will be able to:
Navigate to a draft post in WordPress Admin and review its content
Apply the FNF brand voice checklist before publishing
Publish a post from the WordPress editor
Confirm a post is live by visiting the published URL


Purpose
Review and publish a draft post from WordPress Admin
Prerequisites
Draft post exists in WordPress (SOP-003 complete)
Time required
5-10 minutes including review


Brand Voice Checklist — Review Before Every Publish


Check
[ ]
No guilt language — no 'you should feel ashamed' or 'if you care you will...'
[ ]
No alarmist framing — no 'it's too late' or 'the world is ending'
[ ]
Opens with a fact, question, or observation — not outrage
[ ]
Jargon and acronyms explained on first use
[ ]
Ends with ONE clear, achievable call to action
[ ]
Cause area connections are named where relevant
[ ]
Correct WordPress category assigned


Steps
Log into funnynfunny.com/wp-admin
Go to Posts > All Posts
Find the draft post — it shows a Draft label next to the title
Click the post title to open the WordPress editor
Read the full post and apply the Brand Voice Checklist above
Make any edits needed — fix tone, update facts, improve the headline
Confirm the correct Category is assigned in the right sidebar
Click the Publish button in the top right corner
Click Publish again on the confirmation popup
Click View Post to confirm the post is live at its URL

PRACTICE EXERCISE  —  Editorial Review and Publish
Scenario:
The microplastics draft post has been created by the WordPress Agent. Before it goes live on funnynfunny.com you need to review it as an editor would and publish it if it meets the brand standards.
Your Tasks:
Navigate to the draft post in WordPress Admin
Work through every item on the Brand Voice Checklist
Note any items that fail the checklist and make the necessary edits
Confirm the post has the correct category assigned
Publish the post
Visit the live URL and confirm everything looks correct on the public-facing page
Success Criteria:
All 7 Brand Voice Checklist items pass
Post has a correct category assigned
Post is published and visible at its public URL
You can articulate what edits (if any) you made and why


KNOWLEDGE CHECK
Answer these before moving to the next SOP:
1.  Name three items on the FNF Brand Voice Checklist
2.  What should you do if a post fails one of the brand voice checks?
3.  Where in WordPress Admin do you find draft posts?

Answers are in Appendix A at the end of this manual.


SOP-005  |  Publishing via Command Line
LEARNING OBJECTIVES
By the end of this SOP you will be able to:
Find a Post ID using check_posts.py
Run the publish command with the correct Post ID and title
Respond correctly to the confirmation prompt
Verify the post is live after publishing via command line


Purpose
Publish a draft post directly from PowerShell using the Post ID
Prerequisites
Draft post in WordPress, Post ID known
Time required
1 minute


Steps
Open terminal using SOP-001
Run check_posts.py to find your Post ID:

python check_posts.py

Note the ID number next to your draft post in the output
Run the publish command — replace 291 with your Post ID and update the title:

python -c "from agent_3_wordpress import WordPressAgent; a = WordPressAgent(); print(a._publish_wp_post(291, 'Your Post Title Here'))"

Read the confirmation prompt carefully — verify the Post ID and Title are correct
Type YES and press Enter only if everything is correct
Copy the URL from the output and open it in your browser to confirm

NOTE: Only type YES after reviewing the post in WordPress Admin. Type anything other than YES to cancel safely. This action is immediate and cannot be undone from the command line.

PRACTICE EXERCISE  —  Command Line Publishing
Scenario:
You have a draft post ready to publish but you want to use the command line workflow instead of WordPress Admin. You need to find the Post ID, run the publish command, and verify the result.
Your Tasks:
Run check_posts.py and identify the Post ID of your draft post
Run the publish command with the correct ID and title
Read the confirmation prompt and verify the details before typing YES
Type YES to publish
Copy the URL from the output and verify the post is live
Success Criteria:
check_posts.py shows your draft post with its correct ID
Confirmation prompt shows the correct Post ID and title
Post publishes successfully with a live URL in the output
Post is visible and correctly formatted at the public URL


KNOWLEDGE CHECK
Answer these before moving to the next SOP:
1.  What command do you run to find a Post ID?
2.  What do you type to cancel the publish command safely?
3.  What two pieces of information should you verify in the confirmation prompt before typing YES?

Answers are in Appendix A at the end of this manual.


