SOP-009  |  Adding a New Agent
LEARNING OBJECTIVES
By the end of this SOP you will be able to:
Describe the three components every agent needs: system prompt, tools, handle_tool_call
Create a new agent file that extends BaseAgent
Define at least one tool definition with a name, description, and input schema
Implement handle_tool_call to route tool calls to the correct method
Explain how Claude uses the tool description to decide when to call a tool


Purpose
Add a new agent to the FNF stack to automate a new workflow
Prerequisites
Familiarity with Python classes, SOP-001 through SOP-007 complete
Time required
60+ minutes for first new agent


The Three Things Every Agent Needs
Component
What it does
system_prompt
Tells Claude its role and how to behave. The most important factor in agent quality.
tools list
Tells Claude what tools are available. Claude reads the description to decide when to call each tool.
handle_tool_call()
Routes tool calls to the right Python method. When Claude calls a tool, this function runs.


Steps
Create a new file: agent_4_yourname.py in the fnf-agents folder
Open base_agent.py and read the BaseAgent class
Add the class structure — extend BaseAgent:

from base_agent import BaseAgent


class MyNewAgent(BaseAgent):
    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__("My Agent Name")
        self.system_prompt = "Your role and instructions here"
        self.tools = []  # add tool definitions below


    def handle_tool_call(self, tool_name, tool_input):
        if tool_name == "my_tool":
            return self._my_tool(tool_input)
        raise ValueError(f"Unknown tool: {tool_name}")

Define each tool in the tools list — name, description, input_schema
Write the method that runs each tool — prefix with underscore: _my_tool()
Add a direct run block at the bottom for testing:

if __name__ == "__main__":
    agent = MyNewAgent()
    result = agent.run("Your test goal here")
    print(result)

Test with: python agent_4_yourname.py
Add any new API keys to .env and config.py
Add the agent to run_agents.py following the existing pattern

Planned Future Agents
Agent
File Name
Purpose
Email Agent
agent_4_email.py
Gmail — newsletter drafts and subscriber communications
Social Agent
agent_5_social.py
Instagram and Facebook caption generation from briefs
Analytics Agent
agent_6_analytics.py
Site performance reporting and content analytics


PRACTICE EXERCISE  —  Build a Simple Test Agent
Scenario:
To consolidate your understanding of how agents work, build a minimal agent that has one tool: a tool that returns the current date and time. This exercise uses no external APIs — it just demonstrates the agent loop pattern.
Your Tasks:
Create a new file: agent_test.py in the fnf-agents folder
Import BaseAgent and create a class that extends it
Write a system_prompt that says: You are a test agent. Use the get_time tool when asked what time it is.
Define one tool named get_time with a description
Implement _get_time() using Python's datetime module
Implement handle_tool_call() to route get_time calls
Add a direct run block and test with: What time is it right now?
Run: python agent_test.py and verify the agent calls the tool and returns the time
Success Criteria:
agent_test.py runs without syntax errors
Agent loop shows [Loop 1] Thinking then [Tool] Calling: get_time
Agent returns the current date and time in its final answer
You can explain what each part of the code does


KNOWLEDGE CHECK
Answer these before moving to the next SOP:
1.  What are the three things every agent built on BaseAgent needs?
2.  How does Claude decide when to call a specific tool?
3.  What is the purpose of the handle_tool_call() method?
4.  What is the difference between an action and a filter in WordPress — and how does this relate to how agents work?

Answers are in Appendix A at the end of this manual.


Appendix A  |  Knowledge Check Answers
Use these answers to verify your understanding after completing each SOP. Do not read ahead — attempt the questions first.

SOP-001 Answers
The .env file (containing all API keys) only loads when Python is run from the same directory the file is in. PowerShell opened elsewhere does not see the .env file.
PS C:\Projects\FunnyNotFunny\fnf-agents>
The .env file will still not load even if you navigate to the folder manually after opening PowerShell elsewhere. Python's load_dotenv() looks in the current working directory at the time Python starts.

SOP-002 Answers
[Loop 3] Thinking... means Claude has received a tool result and is now deciding what to do next — whether to call another tool or produce its final answer.
Research briefs are saved to the output/ subfolder inside your fnf-agents folder.
With Tavily configured the agent searches the live web for current news, reports, and data. Without Tavily it uses Claude's training knowledge which may be less current but still produces a useful brief.
Multiple searches allow the agent to cover different angles of the topic — broad overview, specific policy, recent developments, affected communities — producing a more comprehensive brief than a single search would.

SOP-003 Answers
Posts are always created as drafts because advocacy content requires human editorial review before publication. Agents can make factual errors, tone mistakes, or apply incorrect brand voice — a human review step catches these.
Write down the Post ID immediately from the terminal output. If missed, run python check_posts.py to retrieve it.
Permalinks must be set to Post name in Settings > Permalinks. The Plain setting disables the REST API routes the agent uses.
The agent runs get_wp_posts before creating a new post to check for existing posts on similar topics and avoid duplicate content.

SOP-004 Answers
Any three from: no guilt language, no alarmist framing, opens with fact or question, jargon explained, ends with one clear CTA, cause area connections named, correct category assigned.
Edit the post in the WordPress editor to fix the issue before publishing.
Posts > All Posts — drafts appear with a Draft label next to the title.

SOP-005 Answers
Run: python check_posts.py
Type anything other than YES — for example No, cancel, or just press Enter.
Verify the Post ID number matches the post you intend to publish, and the Title shown matches the post content you reviewed.

SOP-006 Answers
Draft, Publish, Pending, Private.
Either the WordPress connection is failing (check SOAP-004 and SOAP-005) or the post was not actually created by the agent. Re-run the WordPress agent and watch for the success message with Post ID.

SOP-007 Answers
Research Agent (Agent 1) > Content Calendar Agent (Agent 2) > WordPress Publishing Agent (Agent 3).
Research brief in output/ folder; Google Sheet for calendar updates; WordPress Admin > Posts > All Posts for the draft.
Review the draft post using the Brand Voice Checklist before publishing.

SOP-008 Answers
KEY_NAME=value-with-no-quotes — no spaces around =, no quote marks around the value.
Python's load_dotenv() reads the .env file when it starts. A fresh window forces a new Python start which re-reads the updated .env. An existing window still has the old values in memory.
The .gitignore file lists .env so Git excludes it from commits.

SOP-009 Answers
system_prompt (Claude's role and instructions), tools list (what tools Claude can call), handle_tool_call() (routes tool calls to Python methods).
Claude reads the description field of each tool definition. A clear, specific description that includes when to use it and example contexts produces much better tool selection than a vague description.
handle_tool_call() acts as the router — when Claude decides to call a tool by name, this method receives the name and input, finds the matching Python method, runs it, and returns the result to Claude.
Actions trigger code at a named point in execution (event-based), Filters modify a value passing through (transform-based). Agents are similar — tool calls are like actions (triggered at the right moment), while the system prompt shapes output like a filter (modifies how Claude responds throughout).

